

Abstract— Requirement errors are one of the most critical factor that crashes software projects. Industry research draws a clear picture. Approximately 40% of failures stem from weak, conflicting, or missing requirement documents. It is remarkable that the transformation of raw stakeholder data into structured documents is still done manually in many places. The vast majority of existing tools do not support Turkish because of its morphological complexity. In this study, we present a new end-to-end pipeline called "AutoReq". The system automatically analyzes Turkish requirement texts from end to end. This analysis is a non-linear, nested process. The Stanza-based preprocessing module is active. It performs sentence segmentation and KVKK-compliant masking, actor and business object, Hybrid FR/NFR classification. Then, the Gemini 2.5 Flash model takes over. The analysis deepens. Conflict detection. Gap analysis. Requirement improvement. The system runs all of these simultaneously. As soon as the analyses finish, it moves directly to the documents. The ISO/IEC/IEEE 29148 compliant SRS document is ready. It generates User Stories, Gherkin BDD scenarios, and the Product Backlog. We obtained a 94.7% FR/NFR classification accuracy on the 244-sentence development corpus covering eight domains. Contradictions were detected on an independent conflict dataset with a 96.1% F1 score. Honestly, the result that surprised us was this. The accuracy dropped to 87.6% in the 113-sentence held-out corpus consisting of fields that have never been encountered before. A significant drop in rule-based actor extraction performance was observed. These results reveal the need for transformer-based NER integration. Still, this first end-to-end pipeline for Turkish requirements engineering is promising from a practical standpoint.

Keywords— Software Requirements Engineering, Natural Language Processing, Large Language Model, Automated Document Generation, Software Requirements Specification (SRS), Conflict Detection, Behavior-Driven Development (BDD), Requirements Classification.

I. Introduction

Did you know that about 40% of software projects fail because of requirement errors [1]? This statistic has been repeated so many times that it is now taken for granted. But the structural problem it points to is still standing strong. In this study, we present an end-to-end pipeline called "AutoReq" that targets exactly this problem.

Boehm and Basili [2] presented a striking cost table. Fixing a bug caught at the requirements stage is about ten times cheaper. The cost grows exponentially if it is caught in a live environment. The industry has known this for a long time. But in daily practice, this knowledge fails to turn into action.

Well, why is it so stubborn? There are structural reasons. Contradictions rarely appear as obvious statements. Conflict arises in real life from the interaction of requirements written at different times, under pressure from different stakeholders. Consider a vague requirement like "It should work fast." It passes review without any issues. But since it has no numerical equivalent, it turns into a design crisis. Wagner et al. [3] examined exactly this pattern in different countries. They confirmed that the problem is universal. The issue stems more from the nature of the process than from the inexperience of the teams.

The existing tools in the literature have addressed specific subfields of the problem. Rule-based NLP techniques can successfully perform entity extraction under limited conditions. Machine learning models show variable success in FR/NFR classification. LLMs are good at rewriting vague requirements. However, they fall short on their own when it comes to scanning the entire requirement set and finding logical contradictions. As far as we know, there is no integrated Turkish requirements engineering tool yet [4]. AutoReq was designed to fill exactly this gap.

AutoReq pipeline passes input texts through three layers. First, morphological analysis and dependency parsing are performed using the Stanza library. Then parallel LLM analysis processes using the Gemini 2.5 Flash model kick in. In the final step, the generation layer produces four different output documents.

The points that set AutoReq apart from other works can be summarized as follows. NLP and LLM integration provides a fully automated workflow. Manual data transfer is not required. The ConflictDetector module does not only identify conflicting pairs. It presents the type and reason of the contradiction with natural language explanations. The most striking point is this: from a single analysis pass, SRS, User Stories, Gherkin scenarios, and a backlog list are all produced at the same time.

The rest of the article is organized as follows. Section II presents related work, Section III presents the system architecture and methodology, Section IV presents experimental evaluations, and Section V presents conclusions and future plans.

II.  Literature Review

Extracting requirements from natural language texts is not a new topic. Studies in the field of NLP have been ongoing for years. Success levels and practical applicability vary widely.

Dalpiaz et al. [6] combined explainable machine learning methods with dependency tree features. They reported over 85% accuracy in FR/NFR classification. A nice result. But an approach designed entirely according to English language structure. Because it can't be directly adapted to agglutinative languages like Turkish. Why? Dozens of inflected surface forms derive from a single root in Turkish. This morphological richness invalidates the feature assumptions of classifiers trained on English. Ferrari and Esuli [7] focused on detecting word-level ambiguities in different domains. A valuable contribution. But it doesn't address the logical contradictions between sentences that are far apart from each other.

The use of LLMs in requirements engineering has gained significant momentum in recent times. Fan et al. [8] made a notable observation. While code generation and bug detection dominate the literature, requirements engineering has not yet been studied enough. Ronanki et al. [9] examined LLM-supported requirements elicitation processes. It raised an interesting dilemma. These models can generate explanatory questions that make sense. But it often hallucinates by making up requirements and producing structural inconsistencies. The lesson here is clear. A system that relies on an LLM without preprocessing and output validation layers cannot be reliable. LLMs should be supporting components tightly constrained by strict rules, not the pipeline itself.

ISO/IEC/IEEE 29148 standard [4] defines the section structure of an SRS document quite clearly. This clarity should provide a suitable ground for automation. Yet automatic SRS generation has received surprisingly little attention. Most existing tools either do template-based static filling or expect the user to enter content manually. We could not find any open academic studies that create analytical representations from raw stakeholder texts and dynamically populate templates.

Conflict detection has a longer history. Guo et al. [10] achieved 83.9% accuracy in pairwise conflict detection using semantic analysis methods. But these systems only classify contradictions in a binary way as "present/absent." Is this enough for an analyst in a real project? Most of the time, no. Knowing whether the contradiction is a logic error, a scope overlap, or a missing precondition is vital.

Ronanki et al. [11] made an important finding in the automatic generation of BDD scenarios. The consistency of the User Stories generated by ChatGPT shows large fluctuations. Without expert oversight, including these in software processes is risky. This finding confirms that downstream output quality depends entirely on upstream preprocessing and analysis quality.

In summary, there are studies in the literature that focus on the individual components of the pipeline. However, no integrated system has been designed that combines preprocessing, classification, conflict detection, and test scenario generation together. Moreover, this kind of integration has not been attempted for a language with high morphological complexity like Turkish. AutoReq was developed to carry out exactly this integration.

