III. System Architecture and Methodology

AutoReq pipeline consists of three layers. The raw stakeholder text first goes through the preprocessing layer. Then it is passed to the LLM analysis layer. Finally, the generation layer converts the findings into final documents. All data flow between layers runs through two data classes defined in core/models.py. ParsedDocument carries the preprocessing outputs. AnalysisReport, on the other hand, holds the LLM analysis results. This strict type checking minimizes integration errors. Honestly, during development we noticed that type mismatches between layers are one of the sneakiest sources of bugs. The application works by calling the central process_text() function through the Streamlit interface.

Fig. 1. Three-layer pipeline architecture of AutoReq.

Preprocessing. This layer uses the Turkish Stanza model [5]. It performs sentence segmentation, tokenization, multi-word tokenization (MWT), POS tagging, lemmatization, and dependency parsing. We disabled the unused neural NER module. This reduced memory consumption to around 300 MB. Application startup speed increased noticeably. Sentence boundary detection is done by the Stanza segmenter component. Each sentence is assigned a unique ID in the REQ_001 format.

Actor extraction works in two stages. In the first pass, the lemmas obtained from Stanza morphological analysis are compared against a predefined role table.This table includes roles such as user, manager, admin, customer, patient, doctor, and secretary. Here is a critical point. Turkish is an agglutinative language. Mapping through surface forms results in a high rate of failure. The analysis must be done at the lemma level. In the second pass, the Stanza dependency tree is scanned. Only noun-type words that serve as the grammatical subject (nsubj, nsubj:pass, obl:agent) or are linked to the preposition "tarafından" in passive voice sentences become actor candidates. This mechanism largely prevents expressions in object position — such as "sayfa geçişleri" or "kupon kodu" — from being mislabeled.

We integrated a local KVKK (Turkish Personal Data Protection Law) masking layer into the pipeline. Before raw text is sent to LLM services, Turkish ID Numbers and proper names are masked using regular expressions. Identity numbers are replaced with the [TC_KIMLIK_NO] tag, and proper names are replaced with the [KISI_ADI] tag. We used a sentence-initial analysis mechanism and exception lists to prevent words at the beginning of a sentence from being incorrectly masked as nouns.

FR/NFR classification is being carried out with a three-layer hybrid architecture. In the first layer, the rule-based functional verb detector scans for modal verbs and simple present tense structures. In the second layer, a regex matcher runs that looks for standard NFR keywords such as security, performance, encryption, and latency. Ambiguous sentences that these two rule-based layers cannot clarify are sent to the Gemini LLM service in the final stage. The interesting part is that the result is quite impressive. This hybrid approach raised the accuracy from 69.8%, which was the baseline relying solely on keyword matching, to 94.7%.

LLM Analysis Layer. The ParsedDocument object coming out of the preprocessing layer is sent to two LLM modules running in parallel with a ThreadPoolExecutor. These are ConflictDetector and GapAnalyzer. The RequirementImprover module works together with output generators inside a second thread pool. Modules serialize requirements in the format [REQ_NNN] (TYPE) TEXT. Input texts are wrapped in <requirement_text>...</requirement_text> XML tags to prevent prompt injection attacks. The JSON format of LLM outputs is guaranteed. The extract_json_object() function is used to clean up any markdown remnants that may be returned from the API.

Fig. 2. Example input–output of the LLM analysis layer: conflict detection and optimization results.

ConflictDetector classifies conflicts between requirements into six categories. These are logic, business rule, performance, security, usability, and other. Logic conflicts cover directly opposing requests. Business rule conflicts target inconsistencies in process flows. The GapAnalyzer module is perhaps the least appreciated but most useful component. It detects missing processes that are implicitly present but unwritten in the stakeholder text. For example, the password change flow may be defined but the "forgot my password" flow may have been forgotten. Domain_references checklists customized according to the system type are dynamically injected into this module. Analysis quality improves noticeably. RequirementImprover converts vague requirements into measurable, testable statements.

Output Generation Layer. After the analysis results are written to the AnalysisReport object, the generation layer kicks in. All document generation operations are performed using in-memory io.BytesIO buffers instead of disk to prevent write conflicts and data leaks in multi-user environments.

The SRS document consists of 11 sections compliant with the ISO/IEC/IEEE 29148 standard. We use the fpdf2 library, which has full Turkish character support in PDF documents. For DOCX output, we chose the python-docx library. For User Stories, LLM calls are made using templates suited to Turkish language structure. Gherkin BDD scenarios group all test cases under a single Feature heading. It produces output that is fully compatible with standard test runners. Finally, the backlog list with priorities determined according to the Fibonacci scale is generated in XLSX format. A small detail: to keep the 8 SP limit mathematically reachable, we had to raise the threshold value to 4.0 and above.

IV. Results and Evaluation

Fig. 4. AutoReq results interface showing detected conflicts with severity ratings and requirement pairs.

In the experimental evaluation, we used three different datasets. The development corpus consists of 244 sentences covering 8 different domains. These domains are e-commerce, banking, education, enterprise, mobile application, IoT, SaaS, and gaming. To test the generalization ability, we prepared an independent held-out corpus of 113 sentences from the health and automotive domains. The system was never exposed to these areas during the development phase. Conflict detection evaluation was carried out on a total of 153 requirements, including 50 intentional conflict pairs and control sentences. All evaluations were run with the Gemini 2.5 Flash model.

Development Corpus Results. On a 244-sentence development corpus, we achieved 94.7% accuracy in FR/NFR classification. Correct predictions were made in 231 out of 244 sentences. Actor extraction achieved 92.4% precision and 81.2% recall. The F1 score was calculated as 86.5%. In areas such as banking and corporate portals, actor extraction achieved 100.0% precision and recall values. Consistent results also emerged in the newly added technical areas such as IoT, SaaS, and gaming. The sectoral breakdown is presented in detail in Table II. One note should be made. Because the expected actor was not present in the mobile application field, the actor extraction metrics came out as mathematically 0%. This is not an error, but a characteristic that comes from the nature of the dataset.

