Held-out Corpus Results. FR/NFR classification accuracy was measured at 87.6% on 113 sentences from the health and automotive domains that the system had never seen before. A precision of 61.9% and a recall of 41.9% were achieved in actor extraction. F1 score 50.0%. We examined this performance drop closely. The main reason is that the current NER module depends on rule-based lexicon matching.

Let's make this concrete. Compound expressions like "radar sensor" or "dashboard" are expected to appear as actors in the automotive domain. However, these expressions are not defined in the lexicon. The Stanza NER module can only extract single words. This situation shows up in the metrics as a matching error. A different issue is drawing attention in the health field. The word "patient" can be used both as an actor and as a modifier in Turkish. This ambiguity negatively affects precision metrics. Rule-based actor extraction is strong in well-known domains. But it reaches its limits in new domains where the terminology has not been defined in advance.

Conflict Detection Results. We evaluated conflict detection on an independent and comprehensive dataset, unlike the small-scale trials in previous versions. Batched LLM analysis was performed on a total of 153 requirements, including 50 intentional contradiction pairs and control sentences. The ConflictDetector module reported 52 conflict pairs. Of these, 49 were correct detections and 3 were classified as false positives. Only 1 conflict pair was missed.

These results correspond to a recall of 98.0%, a precision of 94.2%, and an F1 score of 96.1%. What was the one missed contradiction? It was the indirect scope-limiting contradiction between "dynamic translation of all interface texts" and "support for English and Turkish only." Because there was no direct word-level contrast, it slipped past the LLM's attention. The false positives came from sentence pairs on topics that are semantically close to each other, such as authorization management and security policy.

Ablation Analysis. What happened when we completely disabled the LLM analysis layer? Conflict detection success dropped to 0%. This clearly shows that the LLM layer is indispensable. On the speed side, the hybrid classification flow takes an average of 1.15 seconds per sentence. Only the rule-based NLP flow completes in 0.68 seconds. About 25% of the requests were routed to the LLM fallback step. The average processing time for these sentences was measured at 2.45 seconds. The additional latency of the LLM layer in the overall average is +0.47 seconds per sentence. In single document generation processes, this latency does not negatively affect the user experience.

Software Quality Assurance. We developed a comprehensive automated test suite to verify the stability of the pipeline. A total of 190 unit and integration tests passed successfully. 106 of them are snapshot tests. The average runtime of the test suite is 501.52 seconds. The tests run in a fully isolated and stable manner.

V. Conclusion

In this study, we presented AutoReq. This is the first end-to-end pipeline that fully automatically generates four different artifacts, including an ISO/IEC/IEEE 29148-compliant SRS, from Turkish stakeholder texts. Our hybrid architecture combines Stanza-based NLP preprocessing with two parallel LLM analysis modules. Although we achieved 94.7% FR/NFR accuracy and an 86.5% actor extraction F1 score, the 87.6% classification performance in unknown domains did not fully satisfy us. Honestly, the 50.0% actor extraction F1 score was disappointing. The 96.1% F1 score in conflict detection is a strong result. But the limits of rule-based actor extraction are clear.

At this point, I must admit that the rule-based lexicon approach works in known domains. However, it breaks down in new fields with dense technical terminology, like automotive. The biggest weakness is its failure to recognize compound technical terms like "radar sensor" or "instrument panel." The ambiguity caused by the word "patient" functioning as both an actor and a qualifier element in Turkish is another problem. In short, the current actor extraction module is the weakest link in the system.

Our priority in future studies is clear. We should integrate a deep learning-based NER model trained specifically for Turkish, replacing rule-based actor extraction. A Transformer or BERT-based approach will bring significant improvement in compound technical terms. Both English and German language support should be added. The generated backlog items should be exported directly to project management tools via Jira and Azure DevOps APIs. There should also be user experience studies conducted with business analysts working on real projects. Honestly, AutoReq is a promising start. But there is a lot of work to be done.

